      {
        "paragraph_index": 1,
        "text": "### Chemistry Insight\n\nThe very low (negative) pKa₁ indicates that the first proton of oxalic acid dissociates essentially completely in aqueous solution — oxalic acid is a moderately strong acid in its first step. The second dissociation (pKa₂ = 3.8) is typical of a weak acid. The large gap of ~5 units between pKa₁ and pKa₂ arises because removing the second proton from the already negatively charged hydrogen oxalate ion (HC₂O₄⁻) is electrostatically much more difficult. This two-step dissociation makes oxalate an excellent chelating ligand for metal ions, as confirmed by the 20 different metal–oxalate systems catalogued in SRD-46.\n\n*Source: NIST Standard Reference Database 46 (SRD-46)*",
